						<div class="postbody">Original question:<div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So, is there a technical reason why the total number of colors on the NES is only 64 (52 + a few black entries) instead of 256?</div><br />Elaboration:<div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would understand it if the palettes occupied only 24 bytes (<span style="text-decoration: underline">6 bits for each of the 2 x 4 x 4 entries</span>). But they take the full 32 bytes (8 bits for each of the 2 x 4 x 4 entries).</div><br />One of the answers:<br /><div class="quotetitle">AWJ wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The PPU's internal palette RAM is only six bits wide.</div></div>

					
